      "RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback) has three stages: supervised fine-tuning on demonstration data (humans write ideal responses), reward model training (humans compare response pairs; the reward model learns to score responses), and PPO optimization (PPO — Proximal Policy Optimization, a reinforcement learning algorithm for stable policy updates — the language model is updated to maximize the reward model's score). RLHF was the original ChatGPT alignment approach and produces strong results. The operational cost: you need a separate reward model, PPO training stability requires careful hyperparameter tuning, and reward hacking (the policy learning to exploit the reward model rather than actually improving) is a real failure mode.",
      "DPO (Direct Preference Optimization) reformulates RLHF as a supervised learning problem directly on human preference pairs, eliminating the separate reward model and the RL training loop. Given a preferred response and a rejected response for the same prompt, DPO trains the model to increase the log probability of the preferred response and decrease that of the rejected response, with a KL divergence term (a measure of how far the updated probability distribution has moved from the reference — keeps the model from drifting too far from its pre-alignment behavior) preventing excessive drift from the reference model. DPO produces alignment quality comparable to RLHF at significantly lower training complexity — it runs as standard supervised fine-tuning on preference data. DPO is well-supported in open-source frameworks (TRL and Axolotl — Python libraries that wrap the fine-tuning loop and handle dataset formatting) and has largely replaced RLHF for teams without dedicated RL infrastructure. For your scenario: if you have preference data (pairs of good/bad responses), DPO is the practical recommendation.",
